<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1652,2037]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Latreille" baseAuthorityYear="1796" box="[151,378,1652,1677]" class="Arachnida" family="Argasidae" genus="Argas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ixodida" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vespertilionis">
<emphasis box="[151,378,1652,1677]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Argas vespertilionis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a very wide distribution, typical of tick species specializing on bats as hosts. It occurs throughout Europe and much of Asia and Africa, ranging from the 
<collectingCountry box="[909,949,1688,1711]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">UK</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry box="[986,1050,1688,1711]" name="Japan" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Japan</collectingCountry>
and reaching as far south as 
<collectingCountry box="[1379,1437,1687,1712]" name="India" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">India</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Filippova, N. A." box="[158,334,1724,1749]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" refId="ref41148" refString="Filippova, N. A. (1966) Argasid ticks (Argasidae). In: Fauna of USSR, Arachnoidea 4, 259 pp. [in Russian]" type="book" year="1966">Filippova 1966</bibRefCitation>
; Hoogstraal 1985a). It occurs in breeding as well as transient colonies of bats in habitats including attics, burrows, tree holes and caves (
<bibRefCitation author="Siuda, K. &amp; Stanko, M. &amp; Piksa, K. &amp; Gorz, A." box="[579,780,1759,1784]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="39 - 45" refId="ref66425" refString="Siuda, K., Stanko, M., Piksa, K. &amp; Gorz, A. (2009) Ticks (Acari: Ixodidae) parasitizing bats in Poland and Slovakia. Wiadomosci Parazytologiczne, 55, 39 - 45." type="journal article" year="2009">
Siuda 
<emphasis box="[653,704,1759,1784]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">et al</emphasis>
. 2009
</bibRefCitation>
). In continental Southeast Asia it has been recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[151,266,1796,1821]" name="Cambodia" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Cambodia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Borel, M." box="[284,414,1796,1821]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="328" refId="ref36482" refString="Borel, M. (1928) Note sur la presence d' Argas vespertilionis (Latreille) 1796 au Cambodge. Bulletin de la Societe de Pathologie Exotique, 21, 328." type="journal article" year="1928">Borel 1928</bibRefCitation>
) and possibly from 
<collectingCountry box="[651,746,1796,1821]" name="Vietnam" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Vietnam</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Hornok, S. &amp; Szoke, K. &amp; Tu, V. T. &amp; Kontschan, J. &amp; Takacs, N. &amp; Sandor, A. D. &amp; Halajian, A. &amp; Foldvari, G. &amp; Estok, P. &amp; Plantard, O. &amp; Epis, S." box="[763,989,1796,1821]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="109" refId="ref48149" refString="Hornok, S., Szoke, K., Tu, V. T., Kontschan, J., Takacs, N., Sandor, A. D., Halajian, A., Foldvari, G., Estok, P., Plantard, O. &amp; Epis, S. (2017) Mitochondrial gene heterogeneity of the bat soft tick Argas vespertilionis (Ixodida: Argasidae) in the Palaearctic. Parasites and Vectors, 10, 109. https: // doi. org / 10.1186 / s 13071 - 017 - 2037 - 4" type="journal article" year="2017">
Hornok 
<emphasis box="[860,912,1796,1821]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">et al</emphasis>
. 2017
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Hornok, S. &amp; Szoke, K. &amp; Tu, V. T. &amp; Kontschan, J. &amp; Takacs, N. &amp; Sandor, A. D. &amp; Halajian, A. &amp; Foldvari, G. &amp; Estok, P. &amp; Plantard, O. &amp; Epis, S." box="[1012,1251,1796,1821]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="109" refId="ref48149" refString="Hornok, S., Szoke, K., Tu, V. T., Kontschan, J., Takacs, N., Sandor, A. D., Halajian, A., Foldvari, G., Estok, P., Plantard, O. &amp; Epis, S. (2017) Mitochondrial gene heterogeneity of the bat soft tick Argas vespertilionis (Ixodida: Argasidae) in the Palaearctic. Parasites and Vectors, 10, 109. https: // doi. org / 10.1186 / s 13071 - 017 - 2037 - 4" type="journal article" year="2017">
Hornok 
<emphasis box="[1107,1159,1796,1821]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">et al</emphasis>
. (2017)
</bibRefCitation>
show that most morphological characters are not significantly different between 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Latreille" baseAuthorityYear="1796" box="[897,1083,1831,1856]" class="Arachnida" family="Argasidae" genus="Argas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ixodida" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vespertilionis">
<emphasis box="[897,1083,1831,1856]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">A. vespertilionis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
larvae from Europe and those from 
<collectingCountry box="[215,314,1868,1893]" name="Vietnam" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Vietnam</collectingCountry>
. Nevertheless, larvae from these areas could be easily separated using two mitochondrial genetic markers, suggesting that 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Latreille" baseAuthorityYear="1796" box="[434,617,1903,1928]" class="Arachnida" family="Argasidae" genus="Argas" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ixodida" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vespertilionis">
<emphasis box="[434,617,1903,1928]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">A. vespertilionis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may represent a species complex, with Chinese specimens belonging to the European group (
<bibRefCitation author="Hornok, S. &amp; Szoke, K. &amp; Tu, V. T. &amp; Kontschan, J. &amp; Takacs, N. &amp; Sandor, A. D. &amp; Halajian, A. &amp; Foldvari, G. &amp; Estok, P. &amp; Plantard, O. &amp; Epis, S." box="[386,604,1940,1965]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="109" refId="ref48149" refString="Hornok, S., Szoke, K., Tu, V. T., Kontschan, J., Takacs, N., Sandor, A. D., Halajian, A., Foldvari, G., Estok, P., Plantard, O. &amp; Epis, S. (2017) Mitochondrial gene heterogeneity of the bat soft tick Argas vespertilionis (Ixodida: Argasidae) in the Palaearctic. Parasites and Vectors, 10, 109. https: // doi. org / 10.1186 / s 13071 - 017 - 2037 - 4" type="journal article" year="2017">
Hornok 
<emphasis box="[480,530,1940,1965]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">et al</emphasis>
. 2017
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1652,2037]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
Descriptions of all life history stages are available in 
<bibRefCitation author="Hoogstraal, H." box="[838,1051,1976,2001]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="19 - 26" refId="ref44602" refString="Hoogstraal, H. (1958) Bat ticks of the genus Argas (Ixodoidea, Argasidae), 3. The subgenus Carios, a redescription of A. (C.) vespertilionis (Latreille, 1802), and variation within an Egyptian population. Annals of the Entomological Society of America, 51, 19 - 26. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / aesa / 51.1.19" type="journal article" year="1958">Hoogstraal (1958)</bibRefCitation>
. The male, female and larva are illustrated in 
<bibRefCitation author="Yamaguti, N. &amp; Tipton, V. J. &amp; Keegan, H. L. &amp; Toshioka, S." box="[299,554,2012,2037]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="1 - 185" refId="ref72392" refString="Yamaguti, N., Tipton, V. J., Keegan, H. L. &amp; Toshioka, S. (1971) Ticks of Japan, Korea, and the Ryukyu Islands. Brigham Young University Science Bulletin, Biological Series, 15, 1 - 185." type="journal article" year="1971">
Yamaguti 
<emphasis box="[413,462,2012,2037]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">et al</emphasis>
. (1971)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
